RAKUEN — southern woodland city, founded as deliberate counter-argument to
Midgaard's ledger culture: abundance over debt, rotating stewardship, mediation
over tribunal. In managed crisis ever since.

FOUNDERS:
- Verath Solen: wrote Paradise Thesis; died before first flood cycle; frozen
  as the idealist; Bloom Council invokes and edits him
- Caitha Dunnmark: logistics; expected failure within two generations; her
  skepticism removed from public ceremonies; Dunnmark Letters show the truth
- Orn Fallsbridge: path-guide; selected the site; Ember Wardens claim as
  ancestor

SOUTHWARD COMPACT: Common granary duty, public mediation, rotating stewardship,
open accounting. Bloom Pavilion = where stewardship rotations announced. Promise
Stones in every neighborhood; defacing one = serious social offense. Three
conditions: Enoughness (food/water), Seen Labor, Ritual Repair.

GARDEN LEDGER: Public-abundance tracker turned scarcity instrument. Midgaard
"resettled south" Violet Compact witnesses; Bloom Council accepted it; Garden
Ledger Clerks maintain shadow archive of transferred names and have not
forgiven it.

CRISES (all permanent now): Ashfall Monsoons soured cisterns. Redwater floods
poisoned wells. Canopy fires burned storage. Orchard blight collapsed yields.
Route predation cut medicine and grain. Ration towers, salvage courts, labor
drafts = "welfare infrastructure."

THREE REFUSED PETITIONS:
- Southmark Petition / Ash Plea / Iron Compact Appeal — all refused by Midgaard
- Grounds: ledger non-compliance, route instability, constitutional objections
- Most recent refusal: eleven years ago

CURRENT FACTIONS:
- Amendment Track: petition again; most institutionally supported
- Quiet Separatists: Mafdet/Kowloon/Kiess ties; active trade negotiations
- Preservation Coalition: hold Compact; force Midgaard to confront its role

All three block each other. Midgaard sends subsidies but not recognition.
The city calls itself paradise and runs emergency ration protocols.
